247. Chremetis. Like some other Greek proper names this word follows more than one form of inflexion. Cf. Chremetem 472, 533, Clzremetz' Phor. 1026; but Chremi (genitive) 368, Chremem 361, 527. As for the vocative, there is plenty of MSS. authority both for Chremes and Chreme.

248. quot modis. We do not hear of any attempts on the part of Simo to induce Chremes to give his consent, after the match was once broken off. The reference probably is to a number of strong expressions used by Chremes, which would lose nothing in transmission through Simo to Pamphilus.
